From COCHRANE JAMES SHAPLEIGH Subject Re guns in backcountry no thanks In article Dania Egedi writes In article CSD andy Andy Freeman writes In article Kevin Geraghty writes wrong about the whole guns for protection mindset it ignores the Why If you're not a threat you're not affected at That's the part that makes me nervous Who gets to decide if I am a threat Based on appearance Would someone feel more threatened Actions determine whether someone presents a and I don't carry a gun so much for people cause I tend to fade if there are any about but due to several encounters with formerly domestic these critters ain't scared of folks and can get on staying at and saw someone sitting there cleaning his Softly I backed away and hiked another miles to get out of there I'll freely admit it here I'm not afraid of guns I'm afraid of people that bring them into the I'd count that as a fear of somebody having the sense to keep their weapons maintained isn't as likely to present a The Army taught me to clean any weapons DAILY since they usually need it regardless of whether they've been You'd be amazed how sweaty a holster can get or how much trail dust will get in And I guess you'd be scared of me and my former Explorer seems the advisors were National Guard Special Forces grunts and considered it heresy to be out in the woods without a course usually you wouldn't notice ' They tended to avoid public Of course that may be the way to solve the solitude Just carry a gun and display it prominently and one probably won't see most of the other hikers out there who will be hiding in the Dania My goes in a hip holster mixed in with magazine pouches hold lotsa stuff in them canteens knives compasses and Not so easy to notice in the off chance I decide to be I prefer not to be since walking quietly away from active areas increases the number of non human type critters I James James Cochrane When in danger or in doubt run in This space circles scream and for rent